  "voiceover": "In the Old Testament, God gave Israel a strange command: build me a sanctuary, a tent where I will dwell in your midst. And when they finished it, his presence came down and filled it. The tabernacle was the one place on earth where a holy God dwelt among his people — but his glory sat behind a veil. Near, and yet kept apart. Then, centuries later, John opened his Gospel with a line that would have stopped any Jewish reader cold: 'The Word became flesh, and dwelt among us.' The word he chose for 'dwelt' is the Greek eskenosen. Literally, it means 'he pitched his tent.' It comes from skene — the very word for the tabernacle. John is saying the tent was always a shadow. In Jesus, God himself has come to tabernacle among us — and we have seen his glory. The presence that once hid behind a curtain now had a face. And when Jesus died, that curtain tore in two, from top to bottom. The way to God was thrown open. God did not send a building. He came to dwell with us.",
